Announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate stir last summer.
There is a view that this boson is involved in a mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
And this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by a standard model - our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behaviour of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
But there is no 100% certainty among the physicists that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle at our disposal, which is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data published this week during the Great Physical Congress in Kyoto rather confirms it, but there is still no data to be absolutely sure.
However, let's assume that this is the Higgs boson, because the risk of error seems small, and let's look at what this is really about.
In this world, there is an absolutely undeniable law, according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be circumvented - and do not try too hard, or you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that similar law applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
Next, the physical particles are divided into two categories.
On the one hand, we will find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obey Pauli's principle.
And at the other end, there are bosons, evil anarchists, who don't appreciate anything at all - certainly not this principle, which means they can easily be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the facility (by the way absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in the Berkeley laboratories: the mesons that we leave unnoticed, and the "force particles" that spread the great forces of nature and with which the Higgs boson is likely to be related in some way.
It must be said, however, that these bosons are not as exotic animals as can be expected.
If you read this article, it's because of a boson with an unusual banality: photon, or a "particle of light," which is "carrier" of electromagnetic power.
When particles with electric charge speed up or change their direction, they "cancel" the electromagnetic field at this particular point, similar to the pebble thrown into the pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and thus one of the bosons, "force carriers."
More stable fields
It's also with the Higgs boson, only with the difference that "disturb" it takes another field, the Higgs field, to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; very high energy values must be achieved in order to excite it, like the frozen pond level, which only encompass a very large boulder.
For this reason it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator part as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large Hadron accelerator with friendly bundles is a circle with a radius of 27 km! - in order to develop such energy.
Analogy with an electromagnetic field is once again useful to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
With the electromagnetic field, neither all particles nor all materials react.
Some, for example magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper for example will never hold itself on the fridge.
And anyway, with the Higgs field, all the particles don't react: those that do so have a certain mass, while others (such as photon, let's look at it) don't.
