There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their attending doctors for not making their wish come true when a team of palliative pussies softened their pain.
It must be said, however, that palliative care is certainly not all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, Director of Palliative Care at the Society for Home Palliative Care of the Grand Montréal Area, patients are prevented from treating pain in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives to put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, whether by impact or whether the sedatives are given to him permanently.
We cannot pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
A patient who won't get rid of pain will have more and more access to palliative sedatives.
Patients who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to give me euthanasia," it means "I want you to relieve me of my pain."
