In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are depositories of current account books, controllers, money issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually carried out between two e-addresses by e-mail.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the validity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that exchanged bitcoins exist in a public account book distributed across the network.
The key phase is to write this new transaction into this book.
It is done by solving a mathematical task assigned to computers, the investigator of which, a temporary central banker, will have the right to complete this additional line.
This is the phase of cutting the file; i.e. the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital imprint.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, then "chop up the whole."
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific imprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes will easily check its correctness.
The transaction will then appear indestructively connected to the string of all other transactions; any modification would result in a change of print.
If the user wanted to pay the same money twice in a row (within ten minutes) for the purpose of fraud, the network will only confirm one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned because each of them has a different print.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this remuneration is divided regularly by two, probably by the end of 2012.
So the number of bitcoins in circulation is limited to 21 million, but they can be divided up to 100 million, so the margin space is...
The difficulty of the specified task is also increased with increasing level of calculation.
The network has seen its ups and downs.
