Difficult work on the Egyptian Constitution
President Muhammad Morsi has started another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history because of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, irrespective of the opinion of all the others, that the Constitutional Assembly will approve the final text the day after tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state gave this assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been supplemented many times, weakening the country's constitutional stability and leading to legal conjecture.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country's ambivalence.
From the opposition's point of view, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium," continuing to "violate his word" and "trample the law."
However, his supporters assure that this is a means of curbing the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and accelerating the transition process.
There should be a referendum in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of clarifying the Egyptian text article by article.
It is also a way for the President to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while the whole country is being swept by protests.
As he confirmed in an interview for the American Weekly News Time, Muhammad Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
Especially because this hastily organised vote puts the Egyptian people before the ultimatum: 'You either approve my text or I will retain unlimited powers', which should otherwise end after the new constitution has been approved.
Yesterday, in this special atmosphere, 85 Members of the Constitutional Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most liberals were absent in the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the constitution was declared, they slammed the door saying they had no way of asserting their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities copied their move.
In order to achieve quorum, 11 alternates were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It will not be surprising that the articles of the Constitution have often been voted unanimously.
The commentators continued to argue that one of the few disputes on that day revolved around... hours of prayer when some committee members held the view that the clock in the conference room was not properly adjusted.
The text voted on last night consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, remains ultimately identical to the 1971 Constitution and provides that "Sharia law principles are the main source of law '.
Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental requirements, hoped to replace the term 'principles' with the term 'rules', which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected represents a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy" is argued by liberals who only see it as a rhetorical problem.
According to them, the Islamisation of the constitution is carried out through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which confers an advisory role on the University of Al-Azhar, in particular on matters of checking compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt's expert Sophie Pommiere, this is disturbing, because "persons called to comment are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the beginnings of theocracy in this. "
Liberals' fears are fueled even more by the fact that the next rector of the university should be less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there has been no specific religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulams, but university workers, many of whom have studied in French schools, "underlines Alexis Blouet's concerns, who is preparing work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, they agree that "there may be contradictions regarding the interpretation of Article 220, because the terms used in it belong to the religious dictionary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh '.
And in the future, there may be a question as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to comment on this. "
Yesterday, the approved text, apart from religious aspects, is highly criticised because of the extended powers given to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there was a significant reduction in them compared to the former regime.
Another contentious place: powers vested in the military.
In accordance with the wishes of the military officials, the verification of the defence budget will not be carried out by Parliament, but by the National Defence Council.
Furthermore, civil proceedings will not be prohibited in military courts, as required by human rights associations.
These associations speak of their doubts in relation to the text which they believe is directed against freedom.
The offence of blasphemy is preserved and the insult is still prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article deals with the protection of women, underlining Heba Morayef from Human Rights Watch.
According to it, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on TV last night, manifestations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The citizens of the head of state will then manifest on Saturday.
