Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, Poland was adopted as the 20th member of this European Space Agency as a second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (following the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in a number of Agency projects over the following years.
But Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
The Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I will remind you, for example, of the lecture by A. Sternfeld in the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work Entrance to Cosmonatics.
The ideas of a young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and after years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Award for Entrance to Cosmonautics in France.
The commemorative Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote a series of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-famous promoter of the cosmos and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the dark side of the moon was named by his name.
Already in 1925, a railway dressing was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should have been used to start the dressing room or to stop it.
Information about this dressing room is only known from the period printing.
Since 1933, Polish artillery has begun to engage with missile missiles.
The research was carried out by Komórka Techniki Uarmarjenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfk and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It is clear from the preserved materials that the research has reached the stage of the prakzický examination.
However, the arrival of the German troops has interrupted the research.
In 1937, a design of a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the expert press and in the following year the work of Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietoblub lotnicza by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocký came out.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work, focused on all military applications of missile technology.
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities ended with the beginning of the war.
Further work dedicated to the cosmology appears after the war in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautyczne Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a mention of the company in November edition of 1954 of the issue of the issue, in which there are four more comprehensive articles dedicated to astronauts.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicz, is proposed the creation of a company that will deal with cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway, and it was clear that space research was a prospective field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronaut Society (PTA) has tried to join the International Astronaut Federation (founded in 1951) and already in the autumn, PTA became a full member.
And in the following year, PTA President Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became Vice-President of the International Atomic Federation.
He held this post until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been a major part of the development of a very successful weather missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first start took place on October 10, 1958.
The 1800m rocket was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built and in the summer of 1959 the two-stage RM-2 rocket flight tests began in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was 4 feet long and its weight was about 11,5 kg.
Another development type should have been able to do real scientific work by now - the RM-34 rocket should have reached 14,5 km and its task was to monitor the high wind.
However, in 1962, further developments were suspended.
The first RM rockets were followed by the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32,5 kg.
Three types were developed (marked Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0,4 litres, a Meteor-1B of 0,34 litres and a Meteor-1C of 0,62 litres.
The maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, a Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Institute of Aviation, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting mass of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg up to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later is still to be mentioned.
Poland also participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites under the Intercosm programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
