Movie Argo: When the worst is, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a crowd of demonstrating Islamist students captured the American Embassy in Tehran and captured 52 diplomats as hostages.
They were to be released in exchange for the overthrown Shah Mohammed Rez Páhlavi, who fled to the US after the revolution, who had been the patron of his regime for decades.
For the US administration, the situation did not offer a positive way out - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because it would put the trust of allies in other countries at great risk.
But the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, was unable to achieve.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which later was deepened by the fiasco of an attempt to liberate the hostages by force.
The prisoners of diplomats were eventually released after 444 days, after the Algerian government brokered the negotiations.
Their fate at home has caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment.
The Iran debacle made a significant contribution to losing Jimmy Carter to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film of the directing actor Ben Affleck Argo describes one episode of that history that brought a small victory to America.
Just before the embassy was occupied, six employees escaped.
After complex peripherals, they ended up in the Canadian ambassador's residence.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helping with an extravagant cover story - they went on Canadian passports as film crew members who were in the country looking at locations for making sci-fi film.
Combinations of genres
The plan developed by the expert on "exfiltration" by Tony Mendez also required Hollywood cooperation.
In order for the legend to be credible, the film project was written in specialized magazines, press conferences were held, a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have been kept secret for a long time, the film is based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is a strange combination of multiple genres.
On the one hand, a realistically conceived political thriller, at the same time the so-called "caper movie," the story of a successful stunt, a backstabbing, can be an example of a series of Danny's partners.
In the film there are alternating moods - on the one hand documented sequences from Tehran (in the subtitle sequence are shown iconic period photographs of events and the way in which the same situations were shown in the film - there are no big differences).
On the other hand, light passages from Hollywood, dealing with irony and a slight exaggeration.
And then the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, in the halls of the Bureau, on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed in a remarkable way to restart his career.
The mocked actor became a respected director, and even his acting ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after dark crime Gone Baby Gone (2007) and thriller City (2010).
At the same time, it's the first picture of Affleck that doesn't take place in the director's home Boston.
The feel for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that the director's older films raised above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, reconstructing real events - the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which also mediates the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when history moves out of nowhere.
Affleck and his coworkers achieve similar effects in fake scenes (fake crew on Tehran bazaar).
Too many events in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not offer much in the film sense of thrilling scenes.
He's been working almost successfully with it, sometimes thinking about reality - everything doesn't work out so well there (a scene in which the impending crisis at Tehran airport turns off a call in America and a runway chase seems pretty far-fetched).
But the weakness of Arga is the fragmentation resulting from the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charamant in the roles of Hollywood collaborators, but their characters would deserve more space and are not by far the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film kind of loses a dramatic pull, it's a picture that can be watched with a slight interest, appreciates the implementation and retro style of evocative thrillers of the 1970s.
It's hard to tear it down.
As a reminder of one so far a certain way of living history, as well as proof of how exaggerated the ideas of all-powerful and all-knowing secret services are, but they will suffice.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circus
The server www.bankrate.com, which announces the most absurd banking fee every year, has now decided to launch a competition for "the most absurd regulation or ideas from the EU workshop."
"We were led by the last event where the EU plans to adopt a 40% quota for women in the leadership of large European companies," said Patrik Nacher.
Among the nominees of absurdity, for example, is the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to unify the premium rates for men and women.
Until now, women in the price of life insurance have been favoured because they are objectively less risky for insurance companies.
"Other incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by people by the end of this year.
The vote will then take place by the end of February 2013, "informed Nacher.
The controversial EU regulation also includes mandatory incorporation of biofuels into fuel, which is detrimental to nature, and the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers only because they contain relatively small amounts of dangerous substances, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which has made eggs significantly more expensive this year.
Critics previously also faced a de facto ban on the use of the expression "spread butter" or the elimination of classical light bulbs from the sale.
Quality bananas are supposed to be 14 centimeters
The Union apparatus often decides under the pressure of the trade or industrial lobby, the requirements of which are usually defended by a state or group of states in Brussels (so the Czech Republic now also advocates the demands of its banks by the threat of veto).
The interests of the lobby were also supported by the fact that, for example, bananas of the highest quality had to be at least 14 cm in length in the Union and were not allowed to show "anomalous curvature."
At the same time, the European Commission resisted by harmonising the existing non-uniform national standards that complicated trade.
The standards on fruit and vegetables have already been softened by the EU despite the resistance of some countries, pointing out that existing directives lead to food waste.
Last year's EU regulation may also be the candidate for a victory in the poll, according to which the sales of inflatable balloons must be made compulsory to warn children under 8 years of age that they must not inflate without adult supervision.
The EU has referred here to American research, according to which balloons between toys are the leading cause of the death of children for asphyxiation.
Similar restrictions now apply to children under the age of 14 when blowing in pilgrimage stunts.
Curious ideas are born at home
The rule concerning the European officials themselves - anyone who has an official position in the EU, in view of the sensitivity of the topic for Greece, cannot use the name Macedonia and must speak instead about FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The Bank Charge.com server, in cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, nominated a Union regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of a Member State, in addition to some of the above absurdities.
The EU has set maximum levels of food stocks that could be located in the Czech Republic on the day we enter the Union.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the fixed volumes for preserved mushrooms, for which it was threatened with a high fine.
The poll organizers were also interested in the idea of paying some countries to have no sea and the idea of granting subsidies on request to obtain subsidies.
However, these ideas were not created in Brussels, but in Prague.
"We are handicapped by the fact that we do not have the sea.
