As an argument, he said that a lot of grain was born in our country and as a result of so-called intervention purchases, he was to stand full of warehouses which he had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us hundreds of millions of euros to keep the Czech Republic in port.
Finally, the European Commission came out to meet the Czech Republic by organising a tender for the purchase of grain from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The subsidy was offered to the municipalities by the Ministry of Regional Development, managed by Minister Pavel Nědek (US-DEU), specifically to write up a request for subsidies from Brussels.
