Szabo: "Germans have a bigger role to play."
Germany abstained in deciding to accept Palestine.
According to an expert in relations between the US and Europe, Stephen Szabo is thus balancing Berlin on the narrow edge of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first indicated that it would vote against the proposal for Palestinian observation status in the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis were doing in Gaza.
But now Germany must be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think he's going to support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the Libya uprising in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO pushed it.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance on serious international issues?
Yes, it is.
The reason is that it is changing its foreign policy, away from a policy that was, so to speak, managed by the US, towards German foreign policy.
The situation is all the more difficult because Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans are between two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still settling in, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, like they have in France or the UK.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows readiness to adopt positions that are independent of the positions of the US or European partners in the case of national interests.
I think that Germany's foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. export and its relations with certain areas, such as Russia, China, or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of other powers, and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
Firstly, Germany has a large market in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, they must be careful not to scare away the public, but also the elite in Arab countries.
Anyway, that plays a part.
But I wouldn't want to put too much weight on it either, it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
In any case, however, this plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany's relations with the US been damaged when Germany abstained from voting on both important decisions, for example, when voting on Palestine?
I think that there is a great deal of understanding in Europe and even in the US for the German position.
That is why I do not think it was as dramatic a breakthrough as it was in Libya.
Perhaps Germany will even benefit from some respect.
This indicates that it must be regarded as an international player and its interests must be taken into account.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly spoken for veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These differences have always existed as a result of US internal policy.
I think that the Obama administration seems to have a deep understanding of the European position.
But, as a result of the political situation there, it cannot, of course, hold this position publicly.
I think that the differences in opinion really aren't as big as they always seem.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not very happy about Netanyahu's policy at all.
Is it not difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US, on the one hand, and with the position of the most important partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that's exactly what makes it difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and united European policy, which is not happening at the moment.
They cannot therefore be part of a wider line and must instead drive things forward from their own position.
That's what they do with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take the lead in the future and will push Europe towards a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of its relationship with Israel.
That was always a sensitive subject.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player? Does it even want to take on the lead?
Or is the leading role still difficult for Germany?
Germany is still not used to this, it is still unpleasant, and for obvious reasons it is still difficult to play a larger role.
For example, when we look at the European crisis, every time Germany accepts a larger role, anti-German moods arise.
That doesn't make it any easier for the Germans.
It is actually an old problem: we do not want to be surrounded by enemy countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It has to be acceptable to a variety of neighbors and opinions, and that is not easy.
The US's influence in European policy is now steadily declining, but the EU is currently not filling this vacuum.
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it makes them uncomfortable and it makes them even more popular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America study together the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Moreover, Szabo is a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German policy, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
