"People are still stressed, houses are expensive, as well as education, therefore many people delay it," says the young official.
"Let the others have children.
But it is important for me to rely on my own money and time, "says another, about 20 years old, young man.
Both men and women mention career, stress, and the cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how hard the government tries to force citizens to have children, they are still Singapore, who have the last word about starting a family.
What is private offline is private and online
Privacy.
According to the dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something that has a personal character or "a private life area that everyone has the right to protect against any intrusion."
What is privacy for a man under 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers that he is exposed to when he publishes on the Internet things that he would certainly not tell anyone during normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "something entirely own 'on a personal level and to be" username and password' when it was a social network.
"My biggest secret would not be published," says 10-year-old Jorge in an attempt to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he's had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
"I put nice photos or pictures of us playing on FB.
I talk to friends there, too.
I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine or a photo that made a fool of someone, "he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are related.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I started a Twitter account so I could express my views and write interesting contributions.
I don't know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there, "he completes.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far or fast to communicate with friends," he says.
He says without hesitation that he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended someone unknown to him.
The 14-year-old Jose case is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks, and at the last network mentioned, he admits that he does not know 20 people from his list of friends.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, such as music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them were leading him on to anything, or asking him for an address or phone number.
"If they press me or demand of me, I simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José signed up for the Ask after reading the Twitter recommendation.
This boy is not an alien experience of what is now called cyberbullying.
"Known friends on social media were being blackmailed.
They threatened him and asked for money.
He never knew who it was, "he confirms.
The victim didn't check out of the account, according to Jose.
"You just activated the private regime."
Then explains a series of steps how to set up the account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would publish photos of his friends in unpleasant or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I'd do it if I had a problem or if I just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying, "he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English and a graduate of the field of Education and Education, considers that children and adolescents must understand that the main aim of these networks is to inform them.
It states that: "The Internet was created as a means of finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porras notes that the academic staff of Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and the author of the article Digital Aborigines and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain this phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people born in the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and we are still learning ourselves, "he says.
It explains that this is a difficult subject, "because we ask them to recognise what it is appropriate to disseminate, publish and say, and what it is not, at an age when they are not yet mature for it."
Also, in order to be - as far as the surroundings are concerned - balanced, at a time when what they most desire is to be liked, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences, "adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is is, asking questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do something doesn't work," he adds.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the options: are there things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why are you doing it on the Internet?
Or, "Would you like someone to publish your picture the way you published your friend's picture?"
Do you know what other people publish about you?
When you label people in birthday photos, did you ask these people for permission?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you're doing all the time?
The next point is to realize that they have to behave in the Internet environment as well as outside it.
It's the same rules.
"One follows respect, morality and other principles outside the Internet, and the same should be done on social networks," he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, a first-degree teacher and an educational advisor explain that it is essential that children's parents read carefully the rules of social networks.
"If they understand every little trick, they have a good basis to talk to children about the consequences that Internet account can have.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or published, "he says.
Guardia is of the opinion that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional 'do not talk to strangers' rule.
The South American Summit ends and the Lima Declaration has not been published
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), held in Peru, ended today without a statement from Lima, which was announced and allegedly signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to gain access to a document signed at the sixth meeting of Unasur Heads of State or Government, but representatives of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidential Office, who at the beginning stated that the document would be published after the summit, said that it would later be published on the website of the Peruvian Government.
They further stated that the content was published by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in several short press statements.
Journalists had limited access to information throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video was transmitted in the press room from the Presidential Assembly without sound with a message "confidential session, audio transmission limited."
The small amount of information available to journalists was provided by the press speakers of some governments who were present at the hearing, but not by the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document published during the negotiations was a list of participating presidents, which prompted hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent an e-mail to the media with a "final statement" from the summit, but it is only a statement by President Humal, not an official document that the summit concluded.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of South America and the Arab countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA), and even on this occasion the originally promised Declaration from Lima was not published, even though the press was eagerly demanded.
The official website of the ASPA can be found that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities sought to ensure broadcasting for all journalists, but to completely prevent the flow of information.
The summit ended, inter alia, with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to adopt the judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which addresses the border dispute between the two countries.
The President of Peru Ollanta Humala and the President of Chile, Sebastian Piñera, met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they would respect the decisions of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will begin on Monday by hearing both sides' defence speech to discuss the dispute that Lima initiated against Santiago.
"We will submit and execute a judgment that will resolve the dispute that we are discussing today in this international court," said President Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful settlement of disputes, conventions and international courts," added Piñera and greeted President Hubišek with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the International Court of Justice's decision was published after Colombia adopted the Bogota Pact this week, thereby expressing its submission to the judgments of the international court which decided on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, and Colombia considered that the decision was entirely wrong.
The summit took place without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 after the appeal of President Fernando Lugo at the time and did not attend the meeting.
The host President Ollanta Humala was appointed to open the morning speeches and close the Lima Summit shortly after noon.
The President read the final document, in which he informed that 16 agreements had been adopted and that 31 projects between South American countries had been planned, with investments of $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR's member countries would take "important steps towards the South American citizenship objective for which residence agreements are being extended."
He has informed that actions are supported to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil insecurity and international organised crime, to improve the availability of medicines and the cheap Internet in all parts of South America, and to joint and effective measures against the risks of natural disasters."
When Europe is in crisis, "economic consolidation (Latin America) is not supposed to be a victory, but is meant to expand our productivity and show our nations a better future," said Humala.
"We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve the transport links between the various locations of South America, especially rural and border areas... so that our countries are better interconnected and create new economic links," said the Peruvian President in his speech.
He mentioned that five of these projects concern Peru and the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two other projects concern a better connection with Ecuador, but did not give more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to bring it back to the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
Another issue highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful area that is whole and has good neighbourly relations.
In this sense, President Juan Manuel Santos of Colombia, before attending a regional meeting, said that he hoped to meet with his Nicaragua counterpart Daniel Ortega on Saturday in Mexico to respect the judgment of the International Court of Justice concerning the maritime border dispute challenged by Bogota.
"It is possible that I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," said Santos.
"We will discuss all the solutions, none are excluded, nor is the Treaty with Nicaragua that would require negotiations with this country," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we should conduct the negotiations in the most civilized and considerate manner possible," said Santos.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico to take part in the inauguration of the former President of Enrique Peña Nieta.
In the framework of the summit, the Union Defence Ministers met provisionally to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence issues.
The members of UNASUR are Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay, although the last country mentioned is currently excluded.
Peru is the interim chairman of this regional bloc.
