AIDS victims are now a result of a late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when the result of his test was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was as if lightning had struck me," he said, in the memory of the moment of truth, which the doctor tried to "ease" a little, but apparently without success.
The boy kept it from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his own and began to know about it, with such commitment that he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
It is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV Unit in the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara (HCG), which he came to in 1994 after several fights with disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) since the age of 22, something unimaginable in the early 1990s, where there were many doubts, few treatment options, and more stigma.
At that time, neither the director of the clinic at the Mexican Social Security Institute (IMSS) said goodbye to him, "because he had a cut."
At the time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
It is now possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are a lot of people who don't know about their disease and don't come until the virus has caused the destruction of the organism and unleashed the immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years since AIDS disease has occurred in the world, or at least since the first documented cases, "means a great success that the patient's life expectancy, which starts treatment in a timely and appropriate manner, is exactly the same as in healthy people," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civilian Hospital in Guadalajara, saying that this information was confirmed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and HIV / AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that scientists have come to the conclusion that since 2008 AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the duration of survival and full life depends on the degree of involvement of the immune system of patients diagnosed with the disease, better being those who do not use drugs: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years and people with 500 CD4 cells to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that whoever is diagnosed with HIV at 25 years of age can "live without problems up to 75 years of age while keeping treatment," explained in the interview by the doctor.
To highlight this progress, it should be recalled that the life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years.
Although mortality has decreased significantly in recent years and, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died of AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UN Joint Programme for HIV / AIDS - UNAIDS - UNAIDS yearbook), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
Only in the state of Jalisco 255 people died in 2011 and until this May 187 so far. However, universal access to antiretrovirals has been ensured since 2005.
- Why do people continue to die of illness?
- "It seems to me that the problem is not in the possibilities of access to treatment.
This is how I see it, this is how it happens in our hospital.
The problem is that patients come at a very advanced stage because they don't know the condition of the disease, or at a late stage of the disease. "
It adds a convincing figure: "Nine out of ten patients come when there is already an associated infection. All we need to do to make more impact on the overall mortality is to diagnose the disease before, and therefore we need to offer tests on a large scale to detect the disease to all those who ask for it."
In his proposal he agrees with specialists and officials from the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in the state of Jalisco and directly with patients such as Fabrizio, who came to get tests for a private laboratory just because his friend did it, and despite his low age, he had AIDS disease and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer that is one of the usual complications.
"Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're gonna die, and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather take three times a week," they say, but that's not my case.
Change was for the better, eating healthy, practicing, taking medication. "
To this day, all his parents know is that he suffered from cancer.
"I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I look out for myself and for the other person, "Fabrizio, who has accepted the call to share his experience with the MILENIO JALISCO daily, to motivate those who are afraid today in World AIDS Day with his testimony.
"Let them get tested, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV positive, and if they've already been diagnosed, let them realize they can live like anyone else if they're responsible."
This message summarises the motto of the battle against AIDS this year 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a huge gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, stated by Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who is gathering information about the HIV virus.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places that are dedicated to this task, "there has actually been an increase in the distribution of condoms, we have been given one or two, and today they are giving us packages and hundreds of condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who do not have access to condoms," he said.
Teenagers are among the most susceptible to new diseases.
"What do you want it for?" is a common question full of irony and assessment from social workers, school advisors, pharmacy staff and medical staff that teenagers want to avoid, says the reporter.
He suggested that this inefficient distribution be changed, that condoms are not just behind the counter, but that the hundred be found in dispensers in public toilets, in places where young people often go.
"It's not promiscuity support.
It's not even about "paying them beer and motel," as Governor Emilio González responded to the question of whether he would agree to distribute the condoms in his district.
Such sexuality is not. It is best to make condoms available to those who already lead sexual life, "he noted.
Key Numbers in the State of Jalisco
13.435 cases (12.158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV cases) have been reported.
This condition means fourth place in Mexico in new and detected cases of AIDS and 13th place in relation to HIV.
92% of diseases occur by sexual route, 6% by blood route y 2% perinatally.
It is estimated that about 50,000 people can live with HIV, as there are four to five people who do not know about the disease for one registered case.
The judgment approved by the United States Court of Appeal, which does not recognise the debt restructuring of Grupo Vitro by bankruptcy in Mexico, sets a bad precedent for any national company with branches in a neighbouring country and a solvency problem.
Thus, the restructuring procedures for companies that allow Mexican laws do not seem to apply in the country of stripes and stars, despite international agreements.
The approval of the judgment delivered on 15 June last year by Judge Harlin Hale at the North Texas bankruptcy court leaves Mexican companies undefended against the possibility of confiscating their property on the other side of the el Bravo River.
However, the judgment opens the door to the United States Supreme Court to the main Mexican glass producer, alleging three discrepancies.
First of all, while the judge of this case claims that creditors are to be governed by the United States insolvency law, the Fifth District Court of Appeal, based in New Orleans, says that the main procedure provides for bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
Firstly, this would point to the ignorance of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational enterprises.
In essence, for this purpose, a model law of the United Nations was established to unify international trade law, which determines the American Law Institute by arbitration.
Secondly, the judgment states that, without the vote of the branches of the internal corporate structure, where Vitro's debt to the branches is recognised, the majority required for approval of the restructuring would not have been achieved.
However, Mexican laws allow this possibility.
The fact is that Vitro's case was not the first one in which this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, like Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, for whose internal debts the Federal Institute of bankruptcy guaranteed.
In addition, even after subtracting the branches' votes, creditors - who opposed Vitro in the United States, i.e. "vulture funds," such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not have achieved a majority.
In a vote, they would reach about 45 percent to 37 percent.
That indication shall not be taken into account by the appellate court.
In another way, the court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 - against the backdrop of the serious economic crisis that struck the United States.
In the meantime, González Sada's family company will file an appeal for a reassessment directly with the Court of Appeal in order to make an assessment with full participation, namely five judges, because they initially voted only three.
If he fails here, he will call for a review of the process by higher instances, in this case by the United States Supreme Court.
It is important that the court omitted the document sent by the Mexican Government as amicus curiae, in which Vitro's practice under the Conflict Act is described in detail and it is noted that the company has facilitated itself by resorting to agreements signed by both countries to confront the law in question with Chapter 15 of the United States Insolvency Act.
More importantly, the country has submitted to the principles of the United Nations International Trade Commission, i.e. the rules for international insolvency cases, which guarantee equality for debtors and creditors.
Impact on both sides: punishment for Vitro and the State.
